The new hypothesis, **Poisson Run-Length Expectation**, addresses the core issue in the latest critique (where the previous best model vastly underestimated people's aversion to long streaks even when controlling for repetitions). By modeling subjective expectations of run lengths as a Poisson distribution (rather than the geometrically distributed run lengths of an actual coin), the model naturally applies a harsh factorial penalty to lengthy streaks. This accurately reflects human hyper-sensitivity to excessively long maximum runs without breaking the "single mechanism" rule or requiring bolt-on max-run heuristics. 

